  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks designed to combat money laundering. These laws and frameworks are established through various international organizations and agreements, and they set standards and guidelines for countries to implement in their own legal systems. Key components of international anti-money laundering (AML) efforts include:\n\n### 1. **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**\n   - The FATF is the primary international body responsible for developing policies to combat money laundering and terrorist financing. It was established in 1989.\n   - The FATF issues **Recommendations** (now referred to as the **FATF Standards**) that provide a comprehensive framework for AML and counter-terrorist financing (CTF) measures.\n   - Countries that are members of the FATF or part of its global network are expected to implement these standards.\n\n### 2. **United Nations Conventions**\n   - **UN Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**: This was the first international treaty to address money laundering, particularly in the context of drug trafficking.\n   - **UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**: Also known as the **Palermo Convention**, it requires member states to criminalize money laundering and establish AML measures.\n   - **UN Convention Against Corruption (2003)**: This convention includes provisions to combat money laundering related to corruption.\n\n### 3. **European Union Directives**\n   - The EU has issued several **Anti-Money Laundering Directives** (AMLD) to harmonize AML regulations across member states. The latest is the **6th AMLD** (2018/843), which strengthens AML measures and enhances cooperation among EU countries.\n\n### 4. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**\n   - The Basel Committee has issued guidelines for banks to implement robust AML controls, including **Know Your Customer (KYC)** and **Customer Due Diligence (CDD)** requirements.\n\n### 5. **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank**\n   - These organizations provide technical assistance and assessments to help countries implement AML frameworks and comply with international standards.\n\n### 6. **Egmont Group**\n   - The Egmont Group facilitates cooperation among **Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs)**, which are national agencies responsible for analyzing and disseminating financial information to combat money laundering.\n\n### Key AML Principles\nInternational AML laws and frameworks emphasize the following key principles:\n   - Criminalizing money laundering as a standalone offense.\n   - Implementing **KYC** and **CDD** procedures for financial institutions.\n   - Mandating the reporting of suspicious transactions.\n   - Establishing FIUs to collect and analyze financial data.\n   - Promoting international cooperation and information sharing.\n\n### Enforcement\nWhile international laws set the framework, enforcement depends on individual countries. Nations are expected to adopt domestic laws and regulatory measures to align with these international standards. The FATF conducts mutual evaluations to assess compliance and may issue public statements or impose sanctions on non-compliant jurisdictions (e.g., gray or blacklisting).\n\nIn summary, international laws against money laundering are well-established and continuously evolving to address emerging risks, such as virtual currencies and digital financial systems.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
